WEBVTT

00:04.170 --> 00:06.673
Okay. You'll never guess this one.

00:11.745 --> 00:14.781
Hmm. Mango, banana,

00:14.848 --> 00:16.716
orange...zest...

00:16.783 --> 00:17.784
[GROANS]

00:18.885 --> 00:21.187
Cinnamon, tuna fish...

00:21.254 --> 00:23.056
[SMACKS LIPS]

00:23.123 --> 00:24.824
And you dipped your toe in it!

00:26.026 --> 00:27.560
-Which foot?
-Right foot.

00:27.627 --> 00:29.396
-Which toe?
-Pinkie.

00:31.731 --> 00:34.067
You are a freak!

00:38.405 --> 00:40.540
CODY [GASPS]: Did you see that?

00:40.607 --> 00:42.909
People take way more
towels than they need.

00:42.976 --> 00:45.145
-It's so wasteful.
-I know!

00:45.979 --> 00:47.147
I'm done with this.

00:47.213 --> 00:49.883
Now burn it so no one harvests
my skin flakes

00:49.949 --> 00:52.452
and clones me to take over my life
and steal my fortune.

00:53.553 --> 00:56.189
How do you know you're not
a clone of the real London?

00:56.256 --> 00:58.158
I suppose I could be!

00:58.224 --> 01:00.627
All of her clothes fit me perfectly!

01:00.694 --> 01:01.728
[GASPS]

01:03.697 --> 01:05.298
GIRL:
Help!

01:05.365 --> 01:06.599
Cody, what's wrong now?

01:09.102 --> 01:11.271
That wasn't me, it was a girl.

01:11.338 --> 01:13.506
-GIRL: Hello!
-I think it's coming from the ocean.

01:15.642 --> 01:18.678
-GIRL: Hey, up there!
-Whoa, it is a girl.

01:18.745 --> 01:21.648
-A hot girl.
-Floating on garbage!

01:21.715 --> 01:23.016
[WATER SPLASH]

01:23.083 --> 01:26.686
There's a babe in a bathing suit
and you're focused on the garbage?

01:27.787 --> 01:30.824
GIRL: Hello! will somebody
please throw me a line?

01:30.890 --> 01:31.991
Okay!

01:32.926 --> 01:35.862
I thought the ocean was blue
until I saw your eyes.

01:38.164 --> 01:40.533
I think she meant
something to pull her in.

01:40.600 --> 01:42.268
Oh, it'll pull her in.

01:43.169 --> 01:44.571
Give it time.

01:47.974 --> 01:51.077
♪Oh ay oh, oh ay oh ♪

01:52.779 --> 01:56.816
♪Come along with me
and let's head out to see ♪

01:56.883 --> 02:00.687
♪What this world has
for you and for me now ♪

02:00.754 --> 02:03.323
♪ Whichever way the wind blows ♪

02:03.390 --> 02:05.225
♪ We say... ♪
♪ Hey-ho, let's go! ♪

02:05.291 --> 02:07.360
♪ Oh ay oh ♪
♪ This boat's rocking ♪

02:07.427 --> 02:10.897
♪ Oh ay oh ♪
♪ Ain't no stopping us now ♪

02:10.964 --> 02:14.000
♪Because we're living the suite life ♪

02:14.067 --> 02:16.202
♪ Oh ay oh ♪
♪ This boat's rocking ♪

02:16.269 --> 02:19.873
♪ Oh ay oh ♪
♪ Rocking the whole world round ♪

02:19.939 --> 02:24.044
♪ And we're living the suite life now ♪

02:25.945 --> 02:27.080
♪ Let's go! ♪

02:33.153 --> 02:35.822
So what's your name?

02:35.889 --> 02:37.257
I don't know.

02:37.323 --> 02:39.392
All right, uh, where are you from?

02:39.459 --> 02:41.428
I really don't remember anything.

02:41.494 --> 02:44.030
Mm-hmm, yeah. Amnesia.

02:44.097 --> 02:46.299
I've always wanted to go there.

02:46.366 --> 02:47.801
I love the tropics.

02:49.235 --> 02:51.104
That's Polynesia.

02:51.171 --> 02:55.008
Amnesia is memory loss often brought on
by a traumatic event.

02:56.776 --> 02:58.144
How could you forget me?

02:58.211 --> 02:59.713
I'm Zack, your boyfriend.

02:59.779 --> 03:01.681
[CROWD GROANS]

03:01.748 --> 03:04.818
You know, tonight was the night
you were finally going to let me--

03:04.884 --> 03:05.985
Okay, quit it!

03:07.087 --> 03:08.621
Take you to dinner.

03:09.956 --> 03:11.691
So how about it?

03:11.758 --> 03:13.526
I hope you remember how to say "no."

03:14.394 --> 03:16.062
ZACK:
Hey, don't speak for--

03:17.130 --> 03:18.398
Let's call her Marissa.

03:18.465 --> 03:21.901
CODY: Ah, because it means
"Of the sea" in Latin.

03:21.968 --> 03:25.138
No. Because it's written
on the back of her bathing suit.

03:25.205 --> 03:27.974
-And what a lovely bathing suit it is.
-Okay.

03:28.041 --> 03:30.143
Thank you, Zack.

03:30.210 --> 03:33.380
You're hitting on a girl
we just fished out of the sea.

03:33.446 --> 03:35.248
Hey, she's the catch of the day.

03:35.315 --> 03:38.885
-[CHUCKLING]
-[CROWD GROANS]

03:38.952 --> 03:42.322
Speaking of which, they're serving lobster
on the fiesta deck.

03:42.389 --> 03:47.460
I'm flattered, but considering I just
coughed up a couple of squid, I'll pass.

03:47.527 --> 03:51.031
Don't worry, Marissa. you can stay onboard
until we can find out who you are.

03:51.097 --> 03:53.566
Mm, all right.
Let's find some dry clothes.

03:56.136 --> 03:59.773
There's something weird about that girl.

03:59.839 --> 04:01.408
Yeah, tell me about it.

04:01.474 --> 04:03.109
She turned down this.

04:03.176 --> 04:05.645
Ninety-eight pounds of ka-pow!

04:07.180 --> 04:08.481
Ow! Ooh!

04:13.420 --> 04:16.356
No! I gave you one 10 minutes ago!

04:17.891 --> 04:20.493
Cody! What are you doing?

04:20.560 --> 04:23.897
-This is her fourth towel!
-Yeah, well, there's a-- Aah! [THUDS]

04:26.399 --> 04:29.402
Look, washing fewer towels
will save on energy

04:29.469 --> 04:32.539
as well as reduce the harsh chemicals
that get washed into the ocean.

04:32.605 --> 04:35.709
So I'm asking everybody
to reuse their towels.

04:35.775 --> 04:38.345
Ewww! I don't even reuse my outfits!

04:38.411 --> 04:41.181
My motto is "Wear today, throw it away."

04:41.247 --> 04:42.682
[GIGGLES]

04:42.749 --> 04:44.284
Why don't you give your
clothes to the homeless?

04:44.351 --> 04:46.086
That would be mean.

04:46.152 --> 04:49.122
They don't have matching shoes. Duh!

04:51.725 --> 04:54.227
Don't any of you care about the planet?

04:54.294 --> 04:56.329
Right now I care about my guests.

04:56.396 --> 04:58.832
So if they want a towel, give them one.

04:58.898 --> 05:00.934
How do you look at yourself in the mirror?

05:01.001 --> 05:03.770
Like this, "Ooh,
aren't you a handsome devil?"

05:11.378 --> 05:13.947
Don't you have towels in your cabin?

05:14.014 --> 05:17.684
Only one. Cody won't give me extra
towels to dry my hair.

05:17.751 --> 05:20.286
You don't get this look
from one simple flip of the head.

05:21.788 --> 05:24.924
Okay, commence operation towel prowl.

05:31.398 --> 05:32.599
I'm going back to my room.

05:33.667 --> 05:35.969
WOODY [WHINING]:
No!

05:36.036 --> 05:37.437
I need a lookout.

05:43.009 --> 05:45.278
WOODY:
Whoa! [GRUNTS]

05:45.345 --> 05:46.680
Look out for that water.

05:47.580 --> 05:48.648
Thanks.

05:49.549 --> 05:51.418
Oh, look.

05:52.452 --> 05:54.888
There's a trail of water
coming from the hot tub.

05:57.891 --> 05:59.559
And it leads to...

06:01.728 --> 06:03.163
Marissa.

06:03.229 --> 06:04.631
What's she doing out here?

06:04.698 --> 06:06.332
Hmm, I don't know.

06:06.399 --> 06:08.735
Maybe she went
for a midnight dip and fell asleep.

06:08.802 --> 06:11.171
Must...keep swimming.

06:13.707 --> 06:15.642
She's talking in her sleep.

06:17.310 --> 06:18.445
I must...

06:20.413 --> 06:21.614
Get back to...

06:23.350 --> 06:25.352
She's remembering where she's from.

06:26.319 --> 06:27.687
Back to the water.

06:28.688 --> 06:30.023
She comes from the water?

06:31.624 --> 06:33.393
Don't you get it?

06:35.195 --> 06:38.398
Marissa is a mermaid.

06:40.433 --> 06:44.637
Oh, yeah. That makes perfect sense...

06:44.704 --> 06:46.706
If you're zany in the brainy.

06:48.575 --> 06:49.943
Think about it.

06:50.010 --> 06:51.978
We find her floating in the ocean,

06:52.045 --> 06:55.382
She says she lives in the water

06:55.448 --> 06:57.484
and look at the trail of water she left.

06:57.550 --> 06:59.452
No footprints!

06:59.519 --> 07:00.720
[GASPS]

07:00.787 --> 07:03.790
She's hiding her tail under that towel!

07:05.759 --> 07:07.827
I just want to be a regular girl.

07:07.894 --> 07:09.262
[SQUEALS]

07:11.231 --> 07:13.400
Of course, she doesn't want to be a
mermaid. I mean,

07:13.466 --> 07:15.168
who'd want to live in the ocean?

07:15.235 --> 07:17.804
What, with all the robot squids
and ghost pirates

07:17.871 --> 07:20.340
and unexploded alien torpedoes!

07:21.741 --> 07:25.045
Now don't try to make me
believe in mermaids by using science.

07:27.947 --> 07:30.283
If you don't believe me,
check under that towel.

07:31.384 --> 07:33.687
Fine. If it'll shut you up.

07:38.191 --> 07:39.459
What are you doing?

07:39.526 --> 07:40.593
[CHOKES]

07:40.660 --> 07:42.762
I was just trying to get
a look at your tail.

07:42.829 --> 07:44.631
Yeah, right.

07:44.698 --> 07:47.467
And to think I actually
thought you were cute.

07:47.534 --> 07:49.135
But I am cute!

07:50.437 --> 07:52.605
Any chance you'll lose this memory too?

07:58.445 --> 08:01.514
Cody, what is this?
if you hang up a giant girdle,

08:01.581 --> 08:03.216
this could be my grandmother's backyard.

08:03.283 --> 08:06.386
I'm doing this for the environment.
I don't care about appearances.

08:06.453 --> 08:08.188
Oh, that explains your haircut.

08:09.422 --> 08:10.990
Get rid of these clotheslines.

08:11.057 --> 08:14.794
and if someone wants a towel to dry their
towel, you give it to them.

08:14.861 --> 08:16.596
Fine. Who cares about the planet?

08:16.663 --> 08:17.864
Clean towels for everyone.

08:17.931 --> 08:20.266
Here's one for you and one for you.

08:20.333 --> 08:21.868
Oh, wait, don't use that one, it's dirty.

08:21.935 --> 08:23.937
It's got air on it! Here's one for you.

08:24.004 --> 08:25.505
Oh, and take that one.

08:25.572 --> 08:27.674
Oh, wait a minute, don't use that one.

08:27.741 --> 08:29.175
It's got a drip of water on it.

08:29.242 --> 08:30.844
You better throw it in the dirty pile!

08:33.380 --> 08:35.048
MOSEBY:
That is enough.

08:35.115 --> 08:38.184
Now, Cody, I hate to do this,
but you have given me no choice.

08:38.251 --> 08:40.086
You're fired. What are you doing?

08:46.259 --> 08:48.428
Zack. Look, look.

08:48.495 --> 08:50.463
"Briny Man 417" clearly states

08:50.530 --> 08:54.367
that mermaids
"have tails when wet and feet when dry."

08:55.535 --> 08:57.103
It's a comic book.

08:57.170 --> 08:58.772
Exactly.

08:59.606 --> 09:01.207
I mean, do you also believe that

09:01.274 --> 09:04.944
lobster boy can really
shoot melted butter out of his eyes?

09:05.011 --> 09:06.513
Only when he's steamed.

09:06.579 --> 09:07.580
[SCOFFS]

09:08.682 --> 09:11.751
This does not prove Marissa is a mermaid.

09:11.818 --> 09:15.588
I'll get you proof. I have my
number one agent on the case.

09:15.655 --> 09:17.390
What agent?

09:17.457 --> 09:20.527
[SPY MUSIC PLAYING]

09:25.331 --> 09:27.834
-London's your agent?
-Yep!

09:27.901 --> 09:29.903
You were--

09:29.969 --> 09:32.205
But while I'm undercover it's not London.

09:32.272 --> 09:33.907
It's double-oh dollar sign.

09:33.973 --> 09:35.375
Isn't this a great disguise?

09:35.442 --> 09:37.711
After I put it on,
I didn't recognize myself.

09:37.777 --> 09:39.112
[GIGGLES]

09:40.847 --> 09:43.316
Double-oh dollar sign, what
intelligence have you gathered?

09:43.383 --> 09:46.019
Of all people, you turn to
London for intelligence?

09:47.153 --> 09:48.388
Yes.

09:48.455 --> 09:52.225
I followed the target into the spa
and got the proof you asked for.

09:52.292 --> 09:54.961
Marissa got...a seaweed wrap!

09:56.396 --> 09:59.632
Bam! Mermaid! Case closed!
What are you doing?

10:04.504 --> 10:05.972
What's my next mission?

10:06.039 --> 10:07.607
Get me a burger and fries.

10:07.674 --> 10:08.942
I'm on it.

10:10.276 --> 10:11.745
And shake!

10:14.714 --> 10:15.715
Gotta love her.

10:17.717 --> 10:22.222
There's Marissa now. Let's settle this
mermaid thing once and for all.

10:22.288 --> 10:25.592
If she supposedly has a tail when wet,

10:25.658 --> 10:27.527
throw this bucket of water at her.

10:27.594 --> 10:28.628
[BUCKET CLINGS]

10:28.695 --> 10:30.030
Okay.

10:32.766 --> 10:34.100
[BUCKET CLINGING]

10:34.167 --> 10:35.902
-[SHARP THUD]
-[MARISSA SHOUTS]

10:40.407 --> 10:41.441
Really?

10:42.809 --> 10:44.444
ZACK [STAMMERING]:
Oh-- no..

10:46.112 --> 10:47.113
Woody...

10:48.715 --> 10:51.818
when someone says
"Throw a bucket of water,"

10:51.885 --> 10:54.354
they mean the water in the bucket,

10:54.421 --> 10:56.122
not the whole bucket!

10:56.189 --> 10:59.492
Oh, now it makes sense. Okay.

11:03.129 --> 11:06.166
I am so terribly sorry about
the incident with the bucket.

11:06.232 --> 11:09.269
It's okay. Ever since it happened,
I've been regaining my memory.

11:09.336 --> 11:10.770
-Mm.
-I was swimming in the ocean

11:10.837 --> 11:14.607
training for a long distance race and I
must have hit my head on something.

11:14.674 --> 11:18.078
-Rubbish.
-No, I'm pretty sure that's what happened.

11:18.144 --> 11:21.047
Right, okay. now who should
we call for you?

11:21.114 --> 11:24.584
Um, you should call my coach.
He's also my dad, but...

11:24.651 --> 11:27.020
-He likes me to call him coach.
-Ooh.

11:27.087 --> 11:29.556
He sounds like the hard-driving sort.

11:29.622 --> 11:33.393
I'll say. My father resents
every second I'm on dry land.

11:33.460 --> 11:36.996
-Oh, he sounds cold-blooded.
-Oh, he is.

11:37.063 --> 11:40.300
As much as I want
to be a regular girl, I never will be.

11:40.367 --> 11:42.535
I just have to accept it.

11:42.602 --> 11:44.371
I'm destined to live my life in the water.

11:44.437 --> 11:45.939
[THUMP]

11:51.644 --> 11:54.381
You were right! I'm in love with a fish!

12:07.694 --> 12:08.728
Thank you, Cody.

12:09.662 --> 12:10.697
Did you change your hair?

12:11.798 --> 12:13.700
CODY:
London, I'm Cody.

12:16.703 --> 12:18.304
I like the new Cody better.

12:19.539 --> 12:22.809
London, I need to get
in touch with your father.

12:22.876 --> 12:25.011
You're not gonna ask Mr. Tipton
for your job back, are you?

12:25.078 --> 12:28.181
Because chicks dig a guy in a uniform.

12:30.517 --> 12:33.453
That's my uniform--
Nice belly button, by the way.

12:33.520 --> 12:36.189
Thanks. I keep my key in it.

12:37.991 --> 12:41.561
I can't believe I got fired just because
I care about the environment.

12:41.628 --> 12:43.897
I care about the environment too.

12:43.963 --> 12:46.199
I save paper by never reading books.

12:47.467 --> 12:50.704
And I use $100 bills instead of...

12:50.770 --> 12:52.972
however many $1 bills that would be.

12:55.108 --> 12:57.911
[SCUBA FINS FLAPPING]

12:57.977 --> 12:59.879
Ooh, Woodster, great news.

12:59.946 --> 13:04.484
I've been practicing and now I can hold my
breath for a full 42 seconds!

13:04.551 --> 13:06.353
Mm. You should room with me.

13:06.419 --> 13:08.521
Cody's up to like six minutes.

13:09.823 --> 13:14.394
No, I have to learn to survive underwater
if I'm going to date Marissa.

13:14.461 --> 13:16.896
Zack, buddy,

13:16.963 --> 13:18.832
Let's get real about you dating a mermaid.

13:18.898 --> 13:21.501
ZACK [SCOFFS]: Why should I take
advice from you?

13:21.568 --> 13:25.071
The only girl on this boat who will
actually talk to you is our teacher.

13:25.138 --> 13:28.108
and that's only to tell you to stop
breathing so heavily in class.

13:29.275 --> 13:32.512
I was right about her being a mermaid
and I'm right about this.

13:32.579 --> 13:35.015
Think about it. Think about it.

13:35.081 --> 13:37.884
Think about it. Think about it.

13:37.951 --> 13:39.652
-Think about it.
-Woody!

13:42.188 --> 13:43.656
Why are you doing that?

13:45.392 --> 13:47.627
I-- I was trying to get you
to think about it.

13:49.496 --> 13:52.432
[CHIMES TINKLING]

13:52.499 --> 13:55.835
-Everything about you is so cute.
-Oh.

13:55.902 --> 13:58.705
What are these precious
little fingers on your feet called again?

13:58.772 --> 13:59.973
Toes.

14:00.040 --> 14:01.441
MARISSA [GIGGLES]: I love them.

14:02.575 --> 14:04.978
You don't find them stinky?

14:05.045 --> 14:07.013
MARISSA [SCOFFS]:
I live with mackerel.

14:07.080 --> 14:09.049
Don't you remember
the one who married us--

14:09.115 --> 14:10.316
Holy mackerel?

14:11.618 --> 14:13.620
I remember everything.

14:13.687 --> 14:15.622
Especially our honeymoon in Atlantis.

14:15.689 --> 14:19.726
Our hotel was great. Every room had
an ocean view.

14:19.793 --> 14:23.496
I was so proud when you won
50 clams in the dance contest.

14:23.563 --> 14:26.566
Yeah. But I think it helped that
I was the only one with feet.

14:27.867 --> 14:29.936
I wish we had some of those clams now.

14:30.003 --> 14:33.239
-We're down to our last sand dollar.
-Eh, don't worry about it.

14:33.306 --> 14:35.041
I'll just go back to the loan sharks.

14:35.108 --> 14:37.444
Why don't you just go out and get a job?

14:37.510 --> 14:39.913
How am I supposed to do that?

14:39.979 --> 14:42.882
I take one step out our
front door and I drown.

14:42.949 --> 14:45.318
I'm so sick of that excuse.

14:45.385 --> 14:47.120
I'm sleeping at my sister's reef.

14:47.187 --> 14:50.290
Fine. There are plenty of fish in the sea.

14:50.357 --> 14:52.125
I should have known
this wasn't going to work.

14:52.192 --> 14:55.428
the minute you showed up to meet my
parents with a bowl of tartar sauce.

14:55.495 --> 14:57.497
It was a joke!

14:57.564 --> 15:00.200
Joke, joke--

15:00.266 --> 15:03.169
Okay, okay. A duck and a beaver
are playing tennis--

15:11.578 --> 15:13.046
CODY:
Ah, there you are.

15:13.113 --> 15:16.316
Okay, so I finally figured out
why you turned me down.

15:16.383 --> 15:18.418
Uh, the cheesy pickup lines?

15:18.485 --> 15:19.953
The bizarre bucket attack?

15:20.020 --> 15:21.955
Two good guesses, but no.

15:23.056 --> 15:26.059
It's because we're
from two different worlds.

15:26.126 --> 15:27.427
What do you mean?

15:27.494 --> 15:31.197
Well, you know, I heard you talking about
how much time you spend in the water

15:31.264 --> 15:33.633
and your dad and...

15:33.700 --> 15:36.002
how you just want to be
a normal girl and I get it.

15:36.069 --> 15:39.272
I completely understand why we
can't have a normal relationship.

15:39.339 --> 15:41.708
You know, for a sleazy skirt chaser,

15:41.775 --> 15:44.444
it's amazing how well you
understand what I'm dealing with.

15:44.511 --> 15:45.979
Thank you.

15:48.014 --> 15:52.419
You know, just because I'm human doesn't
mean I'm not sensitive to mermaid issues.

15:53.987 --> 15:56.423
-What?
-Ooh, I'm sorry.

15:56.489 --> 16:00.226
Is "mermaid" not politically correct?
Would you prefer, um...Aquatic-American?

16:02.295 --> 16:04.197
MARISSA:
[GIGGLES] Wait, wait.

16:04.264 --> 16:07.067
You don't really think I'm a mermaid,
do you?

16:07.133 --> 16:09.803
[LAUGHING]

16:10.870 --> 16:11.971
Oh, you do.

16:12.972 --> 16:16.543
But, you said you lived "in the water."

16:16.609 --> 16:18.912
I'm a competitive swimmer,

16:18.978 --> 16:22.615
not a mythical creature
who lives under the sea.

16:22.682 --> 16:24.884
Then, why won't you go out with me?

16:24.951 --> 16:27.887
Well, I'd like to, but I'm in training
for the Olympics.

16:27.954 --> 16:30.023
I don't really have time
for a social life.

16:30.090 --> 16:32.325
So you never have a break?

16:32.392 --> 16:35.528
Well, sometimes I rest my head on my
kickboard for a few seconds

16:35.595 --> 16:36.663
while I'm doing laps.

16:37.997 --> 16:40.066
Wow. You know what?

16:40.133 --> 16:41.601
I'm gonna teach you how to relax.

16:42.769 --> 16:44.337
Is this another come-on?

16:44.404 --> 16:45.405
Absolutely.

16:45.805 --> 16:47.507
But, uh, why don't you give it a shot?

16:50.877 --> 16:52.645
You really think you can help me relax?

16:52.712 --> 16:56.549
Oh, yeah. You know, if the Olympics
gave out medals for laziness,

16:56.616 --> 16:58.184
I'd get the gold.

16:58.251 --> 17:00.987
Well, I'd win it.
I wouldn't actually get it.

17:01.054 --> 17:02.655
Because then I'd have
to walk up those two steps.

17:02.722 --> 17:03.923
[GIGGLING]

17:03.990 --> 17:05.091
Sweaty.

17:11.197 --> 17:15.535
Okay, I have our entire schedule
of the day mapped out.

17:20.874 --> 17:23.443
-This page is blank.
-Exactly.

17:26.146 --> 17:28.081
CODY:
Ever hear of recycling?

17:29.649 --> 17:31.317
That's why I threw it at you!

17:33.153 --> 17:36.856
Now sit back, relax and let your
mind go blank.

17:38.024 --> 17:39.426
Are you practicing your kicking?

17:39.492 --> 17:41.895
No, those are the jets.

17:41.961 --> 17:43.897
The jets have toenails?

17:45.432 --> 17:46.800
You're training.

17:46.866 --> 17:49.169
Okay okay, I'm practicing my kicking.

17:49.235 --> 17:50.870
Training is in my blood.

17:50.937 --> 17:53.406
And gravy is in mine.

17:54.341 --> 17:56.576
Now, stick with me, kid,

17:56.643 --> 17:57.977
and I'll help you through this.

17:58.044 --> 18:01.181
Now, lay back and just float.

18:03.583 --> 18:07.020
Ahh, this is really relaxing.

18:07.087 --> 18:09.723
You see? Nothing can disturb you.

18:11.758 --> 18:14.794
You caught her in the water?
Does she have a tail? Let me see!

18:14.861 --> 18:18.264
[WATER SPLASH]

18:21.434 --> 18:23.370
I gotta stop reading so many comic books.

18:26.806 --> 18:31.111
Oh! What is that smell? Oh, my-- Garbage!

18:33.980 --> 18:36.483
-[MONSTER ROARS]
-[CROWD SCREAMING]

18:36.549 --> 18:39.319
LONDON: We're being attacked by a
smelly monster in hideous clothes!

18:39.386 --> 18:41.054
Run for your lives!

18:44.958 --> 18:46.559
MONSTER: I'm not a monster.

18:46.626 --> 18:50.630
I'm a mutant with a harrowing
glimpse of your future.

18:50.697 --> 18:53.333
If you don't get out of that costume
and clean up this mess,

18:53.400 --> 18:54.968
you're not going to have a future.

18:55.035 --> 18:59.239
If we don't change our ways, this is what
the world will look like!

19:01.107 --> 19:03.309
Oh no! there are no maids in the future?

19:03.376 --> 19:04.611
[GASPS]

19:05.545 --> 19:09.015
Disgusting, isn't it? We'll be living in
our own garbage.

19:09.082 --> 19:13.520
Our species will be forced to evolve
into...this!

19:13.586 --> 19:15.155
Annoying preachy teenagers?

19:15.989 --> 19:20.560
I hope you guys like eating cockroaches
because that's the only food we'll find.

19:20.627 --> 19:22.529
No pizza?

19:22.595 --> 19:25.465
Only for the wealthiest people
in the world.

19:25.532 --> 19:27.600
Yay, rich-future-pizza-eating me!

19:28.535 --> 19:30.170
Me!

19:30.236 --> 19:32.172
But, it doesn't have to be this way.

19:32.238 --> 19:35.675
There are little things we can all do that
will make a huge difference--

19:35.742 --> 19:38.812
like recycling and conserving energy.

19:38.878 --> 19:40.680
The creepy garbage elf
makes a lot of sense.

19:40.747 --> 19:43.917
Well, that may be, but my passengers
don't want to have to worry about this

19:43.983 --> 19:45.185
on their vacations.

19:45.251 --> 19:46.453
Let's ask them.

19:46.519 --> 19:51.057
Would you guys tolerate a wash-when-needed
policy for towels and sheets?

19:51.124 --> 19:52.392
ALL:
Yeah!

19:52.459 --> 19:55.695
And how about glasses of
water instead of plastic bottles?

19:55.762 --> 19:57.063
ALL:
Yeah!

19:57.130 --> 19:59.399
And instead of eight meals a day
on the ship,

19:59.466 --> 20:01.601
we could all get by on, say, three.

20:01.668 --> 20:03.770
[CROWD JEERING]

20:03.837 --> 20:05.171
Okay, okay, baby steps.

20:10.043 --> 20:12.412
See, Mr. Moseby? People want to care.

20:12.479 --> 20:13.847
You just have to get their attention.

20:13.913 --> 20:15.482
Well, you certainly got mine.

20:15.548 --> 20:19.319
Now perhaps we can implement some of your
ideas to help make the ship greener.

20:19.386 --> 20:20.687
Thanks, Mr. Moseby.

20:21.821 --> 20:23.356
And can I please have my job back?

20:23.423 --> 20:26.059
Sure. Now the first thing
I need you to do is

20:26.126 --> 20:27.861
take this garbage back to the trash room.

20:27.927 --> 20:29.262
Trash room?

20:29.329 --> 20:31.031
I got this from under Woody's bed.

20:31.831 --> 20:34.200
-I'm filthy.
-I'm filthy rich.

20:34.267 --> 20:35.502
[CHUCKLES]

20:41.107 --> 20:43.877
You see how much better
that was than taking the stairs?

20:43.943 --> 20:47.681
I sure do. I had no idea there were
so many ways to do nothing.

20:47.747 --> 20:48.948
You should write a book.

20:49.015 --> 20:51.418
Uh, uh, uh! Typing.

20:51.484 --> 20:53.019
Of course. Pffft!

20:53.086 --> 20:55.388
MOSEBY:
Oh, Marissa, your father's on the phone.

20:57.323 --> 20:59.926
Hi, coach. Yeah, I'm fine. How's Mom?

21:02.295 --> 21:03.363
No, I haven't been swimming.

21:03.430 --> 21:05.331
-I've been relaxing.
-Good for you.

21:06.266 --> 21:07.534
Well, I don't care if you don't like it.

21:07.600 --> 21:08.668
-I do.
-You tell him.

21:08.735 --> 21:10.170
-That's why I'm quitting swimming.
-Right.

21:10.236 --> 21:11.604
-Bye.
-Wait, what?

21:13.873 --> 21:15.675
Why are you quitting swimming?

21:15.742 --> 21:18.878
Because you've shown me
how much fun it is to sit and do nothing.

21:18.945 --> 21:22.582
Well, yeah, for a couple of days,
but not all the time.

21:22.649 --> 21:24.184
You do.

21:24.250 --> 21:27.787
That's because I don't have
any special talent or drive or ambition.

21:27.854 --> 21:29.823
Wow, I'm a loser.

21:31.257 --> 21:33.393
-And your point was?
-ZACK: Oh...

21:33.460 --> 21:37.597
I mean, look. You've trained
your whole life to be the best.

21:37.664 --> 21:39.366
Don't just throw it away.

21:39.432 --> 21:42.035
MARISSA [SIGHS]:
But, it's so much pressure.

21:42.102 --> 21:48.174
Okay, well, then tell your dad sometimes
you need to stop swimming and just float.

21:49.743 --> 21:50.877
Maybe you're right.

21:51.778 --> 21:53.747
You know what, Zack? You do have a talent.

21:53.813 --> 21:54.948
You're a great friend.

21:55.815 --> 21:57.617
Oh, no, not the friend speech.

21:58.518 --> 22:00.720
Only until I win the Olympics.

22:00.787 --> 22:03.456
and then I'll be looking
for someone to celebrate with.

22:03.523 --> 22:05.458
-All right. then you know what I say?
-Hmm?

22:05.525 --> 22:08.795
Go for the gold and swim back here
as fast as you can.

22:10.263 --> 22:12.132
-CODY: Hey, guys.
-Aah! Monster!

22:12.198 --> 22:13.967
[WHIMPERS]

22:17.237 --> 22:20.340
He believes in a lot
of mythical creatures doesn't he?

22:20.407 --> 22:23.309
He also believes he's going
to graduate high school.
